711924f-c.text:
(1)
Church of the Transfiguration (Protestant Episcopal), 1-9 East 29th Street, adjoining the N. E. corner of Fifth Avenue. This is better known by its popular name, 'The Little Church around the Corner, the origin of which is already a legend. Construction was begun 1850, and continued whenever additional space was needed and the money for building could be obtained. This has given the church
rambling appearance.
April 28, 1932.
P. L. Sperr.

708469f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, between 29th and 30th Streets and vicinity, showing prominently the steeple atop the Marble Collegiate Church (Dutch Reformed). This edifice is located at the N. W. corner of the Avenue and West 29th Street and is viewed across buildings east of same. To the left and right respectively (View 1) are the Burton Building and the Holland Building (formerly the Holland House). The first is at the N. E. corner of 29th, and the second at the S. W. corner of 30th Street. The photographers vantage point is the business structure at the N. W. corner of Madison Avenue and East 30th Street.

View 2 is similar, from the building at the N.E. corner and across Madison Avenue. The vantage point of the preceding view is the building on the right.

August 2, 1930
Views 1, 2

P. L. Sperr
